If you've already included the `<string>` library (or any other header file) in a header file that is then included in your `.cpp` file, you do not need to include it again in the `.cpp` file. When you include a header file in a `.cpp` file, all the contents of that header file, including any headers it itself includes (`<string>` in this case), become part of the `.cpp` file's compilation unit.

### How It Works
The `#include` directive essentially copies the entire content of the included file into the place where the directive is. This means that if your header file (let's call it `MyHeader.h`) contains `#include <string>`, and your `.cpp` file includes `MyHeader.h`, then it's as if you've directly written `#include <string>` at the top of your `.cpp` file.

### Example
**MyHeader.h**
```cpp
#ifndef MY_HEADER_H
#define MY_HEADER_H

#include <string>

// Declarations that use std::string
void someFunction(const std::string& arg);

#endif // MY_HEADER_H
```

**MyProgram.cpp**
```cpp
#include "MyHeader.h"

// You can use std::string here without including <string> again
void someFunction(const std::string& arg) {
    // Implementation that uses std::string
}
```

In this example, `MyProgram.cpp` can use `std::string` directly because it includes `MyHeader.h`, which already includes `<string>`. There's no need to include `<string>` again in `MyProgram.cpp`.

### Best Practices
While including a library multiple times generally doesn't cause problems due to header guards (`#ifndef`, `#define`, `#endif`), it's a good practice to include standard library headers in each file that directly uses them. This makes each file more self-contained and clearer to readers which dependencies it has. However, for larger, more complex projects, minimizing redundant includes can help keep compilation times down. Balancing these considerations is part of designing a maintainable project.

